 on the floor of his nest, a smallish cavern tucked away in a little used part of the grange that nobody wanted.  A seam of lava flowed nearby from the Lavastorm Mountains, heating the tiny space to a degree that was uncomfortable to the Teir’Dal, but a welcome semblance of home to the Iksar.  Incense burned in various corners, mixing with the steam of the place and making vision, even the ultravision of the Teir’Dal difficult.<br>
<br>
To an outside observer, one would have mistaken the lizard for a statue, or a recently deceased specimen.  Only once per hour did the Iksar breathe, and his heart beat so softly, one could hardly detect it using a gnome’s tinkered listening device.<br>
<br>
Only his arm belied life.  Not through its movement, but by the softly glowing tattoo of a dragon that wound its way around his bicep.  Looking closely, the Teir’Dal (or indeed, anybody visiting Neriak 3rd Gate in the heart of the city) would recognize it as the Dragon of Hate, a statue of which could be found over the rogue’s guild.  As it pulsed redly in the dim light, one could fancy it seemed to writhe and change positions ever so slightly.<br>
<br>
The tattoo, or more accurately, the magical ward on Vresk’s arm was also a note of mystery within the guild.  It had only recently appeared.  In fact, nobody recalled seeing it before he disappeared a month or so ago, a victim of some obscure plot of the Plaguebringer’s.  To those few who knew him well, it was obviously a source of immense pain, for the monk’s normally unreadable façade was occasionally broken by a subconscious wince.<br>
<br>
On one occasion, somebody, one of the servants who had gotten careless, brushed up against it.  There was a howl of agony from the wretched elf, and a large amount of confusion.  Examination of the arm where contact with the ward had been made revealed that the flesh had been instantly frozen solid.  As time passed, the freezing spread through the creature’s body, and the local necromancers had found it necessary to amputate the servant’s arm for “further study.”  It was a shame the elf didn’t survive the procedure, but it was a small price to pay for the sake of knowledge.  The results of the necromancer’s tests have yet to be revealed, but it is generally noted that touching the ward is a poor decision.<br>
<br>
----------------------------<br>
<br>
Within Vresk’s own mind, turmoil reigned supreme.  He was of two minds of late, feeling himself torn between the Hate he had embraced and the Fear he was born to serve.<br>
<br>
In the landscape created by his own psyche, the normally placid vista of the Lavastorm Mountains (odd how he had created the place mentally even before knowing such a place actually existed in Norrath) was torn by evidence of battle.  Two towering figures, both of them giant-sized versions of the monk, fought and battled with each other.  Entire mountains had crumbled at the fury of the two.  And in between them was Vresk himself, normal sized, and alternately pleading and screaming at the two of them to stop the nonsense.<br>
<br>
He had taken many wounds from collateral damage, and knew that if this did not stop, that if the peace did not return to his soul, he would be destroyed.  He knew also that being killed within the confines of his private space, his spirit would be broken, and he would never awake from his meditations.<br>
<br>
Failure, as always, was not an option.<br>
